```{r}
library(tidyverse)
library(patchwork)
```


Let's write our first function!
```{r}
cube_it <- function(cube_me){
  # Function computes the cube of the input
  # Inputs: cube_me is the value to cube
  # Output: the cube of cube_me
  
  cube_me^3
  
}
```


Let's test our function out
```{r}
cube_it(5)
```
```{r}
cube_it(cube_me = 5)
```

Let's create a bit more complex of a function
```{r}
pow_it <- function(base_val, exp_val){
  # Function raises an input value to a specified power
  ### inputs
  # base_val: value to be raised to a power
  # exp_val: is the power to raise base_val with
  
  ### outputs
  # base_val raised to exp_val
  
  base_val^exp_val
  
}
```


```{r}
pow_it(2, 3)
```

```{r}
pow_it(3,2)
```
```{r}
pow_it(base_val = 2, exp_val = 3)
```
```{r}
pow_it(3,2)
pow_it(exp_val = 3, base_val = 2)
```


```{r}
celsius_converter <- function(fahrenheit_val){
  
  (fahrenheit_val-32)*(5/9)
  
}
```

```{r}
celsius_converter(fahrenheit_val = 32)
```

## Variables and scoping
Argument defaults

```{r}
pow_it(base_val = 3, exp_val = 4)
```

```{r}
pow_it(base_val = 3)
```

```{r}
pow_it_new <- function(base_val, exp_val = 1){
  
  my_output <- base_val^exp_val
  
  my_output
}
```

```{r}
pow_it_new(base_val = 3, exp_val = 4)
```
```{r}
pow_it_new(base_val = 3)
```
